87","1351":"1351","1291":"1291","1290":"1290","1303":"1303","1259":"1259","1225":"1225","1235":"1235","1245":"1245","1266":"1266","1310":"1310","1233":"1233","1189":"1189","Hilton, Durham, England":"Hilton, Durham, England","Winestead, Yorkshire, England":"Winestead, Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Swine, Yorkshire, England":"Swine, Yorkshire, England"},"en":{"1235–1310":"1235–1310","1225–Male":"1225–Deceased","1245–Female":"1245–Deceased","1290–1351":"1290–1351","–1291":"–1291","–1303":"–1303","1187–1242":"1187–1242","1189–1233":"1189–1233","before 1225":"before 1225","1242":"1242","1187":"1187","1351":"1351","1291":"1291","1290":"1290","1303":"1303","1259":"1259","1225":"1225","1235":"1235","1245":"1245","1266":"1266","1310":"1310","1233":"1233","1189":"1189","Hilton, Durham, England":"Hilton, Durham, England","Winestead, Yorkshire, England":"Winestead, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Swine, Yorkshire, England":"Swine, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Hilton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lancashire):","habitational name from any of various places called Hilton (e.g. in Cambridgeshire, Derbyshire, Staffordshire, North Yorkshire, and Westmorland), most of which derive from Old English <i>hyll</i> ‘hill’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’, though some come from Old English <i>helde</i> ‘slope’ + <i>tūn</i>.","occasionally, as in the case of Ralph <i>filius Hilton</i> (Yorkshire 1219), perhaps from the personal name <i>Hilton</i>, itself a possible form of Norman <i>Hildun</i>, composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>hild</i> ‘strife, battle’ + <i>hūn</i> ‘bear cub’. Compare   Hilt  . This English surname is present in Ireland (mainly taken to Ulster in the early 17th century, though recorded earlier in Dublin)."],"variants":[{"name":"Hylton","meanings":["English (Norfolk): variant of   Hilton  ."]},{"name":"Hulton","meanings":["English (Lancashire): habitational name from Hulton (Lancashire) or Hulton (Staffordshire), both from Old English <i>hyll</i> ‘hill’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. Compare   Hilton  ."]},{"name":"Hilt","meanings":["German: from a short form of   Hildebrand   or some other compound ancient Germanic name formed with <i>hild</i> ‘strife, battle’ as the first element. See   Hild  .","English (London): from the Middle English personal name <i>Hilte</i>, ultimately from ancient Germanic <i>Helto</i>, probably from <i>halith-</i> ‘hero’."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":24,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":55,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert de Hilton was born in 1235, in Hilton, Durham, England, United Kingdom, his father, Alexander de Hilton, was 48 and his mother, Agnes de Verley, was 46. He married Joan Britton in 1266, in Hilton, Durham, England. They were the parents of at least 3 sons. He died in 1310, in Hilton, Durham, England, at the age of 75."},"et":{"1235–1310":"1235–1310","1225–Male":"1225–Surnud","1245–Female":"1245–Surnud","1290–1351":"1290–1351","–1291":"–1291","–1303":"–1303","1187–1242":"1187–1242","1189–1233":"1189–1233","before 1225":"enne 1225","1242":"1242","1187":"1187","1351":"1351","1291":"1291","1290":"1290","1303":"1303","1259":"1259","1225":"1225","1235":"1235","1245":"1245","1266":"1266","1310":"1310","1233":"1233","1189":"1189","Hilton, Durham, England":"Hilton, Durham, England","Winestead, Yorkshire, England":"Winestead, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Swine, Yorkshire, England":"Swine, Yorkshire, England"},"fi":{"1235–1310":"1235–1310","1225–Male":"1225–Kuollut","1245–Female":"1245–Kuollut","1290–1351":"1290–1351","–1291":"–1291","–1303":"–1303","1187–1242":"1187–1242","1189–1233":"1189–1233","before 1225":"ennen vuot